For a native Hindi speaker, those t&#39;s and d&#39;s are as different as any
of the consonants in English are to us. It&#39;s not a bit subtle.
Remember, they are represented by different letters in their alphabet.
(By the way, given that there are some 6000 languages in the world,
what are the odds that two of us on this list would reply to you
nearly at the same time with the same example from the same language?)

I&#39;ve never studied Chinese--I&#39;ve only observed a thing or two from
listening to Chinese friends over the years. My guess is that &#39;l&#39; and
&#39;r&#39; are not contrasted for them at all, so they have no clue where to
place their tongues for the two sounds when they begin to study
English.

Likewise, I can only understand what you are saying about Awl and On
in a theoretical sense. I&#39;m sure I could learn it with practice, but
it would not be easy. When people say &quot;I can&#39;t hear the difference&quot;
between two sounds, they mean exactly what they say.

Ted


